      <p>The Ilocanos are the 3rd largest Filipino ethnolinguistic group. Ilocano loosely translated to "from the bay." They initially settled Ilocos Norte, but can now be found in modern-day Cagayan Valley and Cordillera in Northern Luzon, and
        parts of Central Luzon. The Ilocanos are believed to be distant descendants of Taiwanese settlers. They were animists and believed in spirits called anitos. Their creation story revolves around a primordial giant named Angalo, who was also
        the first man and the son of a god. They speak Ilocano and once had a writing system called Kuri-tan.</p>
