      <h2>Tausug</h2>
      <p>The Tausug called themselves people of the river. They lived in communities called <span class="italicized">banwa</span> and were led by spiritual leaders called <span class="italicized">panglima</span>. Though united by a common language, each banwa was independent. In 1380 <a tabindex="0" class="italicized info-pop" role="button" data-toggle="popover" data-trigger="focus" data-content="According to local lore, he was a Muslim trader and preacher who built Sheik Karimol Makhdum Mosque, the oldest mosque in the Philippines">Karimol Makhdun</a> arrived in
        the Sulu archipelago, introducing Islam to the Philippine islands. By 1450, the Tausug people united and became a Sultanate though they retained some of their animist beliefs. They, along with their Muslim allies, waged war against the
        Spanish, stymieing their colonization of Mindanao. Today, the Tausug are also found in Malaysia and Indonesia.</p>
